    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-03-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-03-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="1001"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1001">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00112A E W/3–1246: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Pawley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-03-12">March 12,
                            1946</date>.<lb/>[Received March 21—11:47 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss>–146. Reference circular secret airgram of March
                    4, 1946, 9:25 a.m.<note n="45" xml:id="d1001fn45">Not printed.</note> requesting
                    a report on the current status of each of the spearhead firms.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Appproximately one dozen firms on the prevailing List are still operating, but
                    all of them are firms locally recognized as Peruvian or as of friendly nations
                    (such as Mandl<note n="46" xml:id="d1001fn46">Fritz Mandl; see telegrams 1348,
                        June 26, 1945 and 3115, December 13, 1945, from Buenos Aires, <ref
                            target="frus1945v09#pg_463">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1945, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ix</hi>, pp. 463</ref> and <ref
                            target="frus1945v09#pg_493">493</ref>, respectively.</note>), against
                    whom drastic action never has been taken and quite certainly never will be.
                    Apart from these so-called Peruvian firms or firms of friendly nations, the
                    prestige of the Proclaimed List remains comparatively high, but of course with
                    the tendency to pay less and less attention to it as the war feeling recedes.
                    The Embassy is of the opinion that complete withdrawal of the Proclaimed List on
                    May 8 will definitely be in the best interests of both countries.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Pawley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
